<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1] St. Kitts: first report
[2] Thailand: (Khon Kaen), spread

******
[1] Papaya ringspot virus - St. Kitts: first report
Date: Mon 8 Oct 2007
Source: British Society for Plant Pathology, New Disease Reports
(NDR) vol. 16 [edited]
<http://www.bspp.org.uk/ndr/jan2008/2007-88.asp>


Outbreak of _Papaya ringspot virus_ in papaya orchards in St. Kitts
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Fruit tree production has become increasingly more important in the
agricultural industry of St. Kitts. This is because of an increasing
demand for local fruits resulting from an expanding local tourism
sector. Papayas (_Carica papaya_), along with bananas and mangoes,
are commonly grown to provide the sector with the 'Kittian fruit plate'.

Mosaic symptoms on leaves and ringspot blemishes on fruits were
observed on papaya trees in orchards at 2 locations along the
northwest coast of St. Kitts (Brimstone Hill and Fahies). Samples
were tested by double-antibody sandwich enzyme-linked immunosorbent
assay (DAS-ELISA) for _Papaya ringspot virus_ (PRSV). In addition,
crude sap extracts from affected leaf samples were mechanically
inoculated onto papaya seedlings. Symptoms typical of PRSV, including
vein clearing followed by mosaic development and leaf distortions,
were observed in the inoculated plants within 2 weeks. All original
samples and the indicator plants tested positive in DAS-ELISA.

Reverse transcriptase polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) for PRSV was
positive with samples from both locations. The nucleotide sequences
of the 2 RT-PCR products were 99 percent identical and showed high
nucleotide similarities (90 to 97 percent) with PRSV isolates from
Jamaica, Cuba, Florida, and Brazil, and a lower similarity of 89
percent with an isolate from Puerto Rico.

This is the 1st confirmed report of PRSV in St. Kitts. Despite
eradication measures and destruction of the infected crop, the
pathogen has subsequently spread throughout the island, wiping out
approximately 90 percent of production.

[M. Chin et al]

